conflicts of interest and physician prescribing of mental health medications utilization of antidepressants stimulants and ant page 1 conflicts of interest and physician prescribing of mental health medications utilization of antidepressants stimulants and antipsychotics has increased substantially over the past decade with the aid of aggressive marketing mental health medications are now among the best selling classes of drugs in the united states in an effort to promote evidence based medicine and lower health care costs states and medical schools have recently implemented policies to regulate pharmaceutical marketing and reduce conflicts of interests in medicine this talk examines the effect of conflict of interest policies in two institutional arenas in medical schools and in states on the propensity of physicians to adopt newly marketed mental health medications in states where pharmaceutical marketing is strictly regulated physicians are significantly less likely to prescribe newly marketed medications and more likely to be influenced by peer behavior
